The paper deals with link prediction in social networks, which is a problem in computational social science. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the problem of attacking similarity-based link prediction, which involves manipulating observed information about the network, making cs.SD (Software Engineering and Security) and cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also involves algorithmic investigations and complexity analysis, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper provides principled and empirically effective algorithms, which suggests cs.LG (Machine Learning) as a possible sub-category.
